AN ACT relating to the support of children; revising the duties of the Administrator
of the Division of Welfare and Supportive Services of the Department
of Health and Human Services; revising certain procedures and
requirements relating to the collection of support of children;
requiring the collecting and reporting of certain demographic
information; and providing other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing federal law requires each state to establish procedures under which the state has
2 the authority to withhold or suspend, or to restrict, the use of driver’s licenses and
3 professional, occupational and recreational licenses of a person who: (1) has failed, after
4 receiving notice, to comply with a subpoena or warrant relating to paternity or child support
5 proceedings; or (2) is in arrears in the payment of support for one or more children. (42 U.S.C.
6 § 666) Existing law requires the district attorney or other public agency collecting support for
7 children to report to the Department of Motor Vehicles the name of a person who has, after
8 receiving notice, failed to comply with a subpoena or warrant relating to paternity or child
9 support proceedings or who is in arrears in the payment of support for one or more children.
10 (NRS 425.510) After receiving such a report, existing law requires the Department to suspend
11 the driver’s license and, if applicable, the motorcycle driver’s license of the person. (NRS
12 483.443, 486.165)
13 Section 1 of this bill authorizes, rather than requires, the district attorney or other public
14 agency to provide such a report to the Department of Motor Vehicles. However, section 1
15 prohibits such a report from being made to the Department if the suspension of the driver’s
16 license and motorcycle driver’s license of the person named in the report would be an
17 impediment to his or her present or potential employment. Section 1 also provides that, for the
18 purposes of issuing such a report to the Department, a person is not in arrears in the payment
19 of support for one or more children unless the person: (1) is delinquent for not less than [6] 3
20 months in support payments or any payments ordered by a court for arrearages in such
21 payments; or (2) has failed to provide medical insurance for a child as required by a court
22 order. Section 1 also requires each district attorney or other public agency: (1) to collect
23 and maintain certain demographic data concerning persons who were sent a notice
24 concerning a subpoena, warrant or arrearage, and persons whose names were reported
25 to the Department; and (2) to annually submit a report to the Legislature concerning

