26 such data. Section 5 of this bill makes a conforming change to clarify the applicability of
27 provisions governing when a person is in arrears for the support of one or more children for
28 the purposes of other provisions providing for the suspension of professional, occupational
29 and recreational licenses.
30 Under existing law, whenever a district attorney or other public agency collecting support
31 for children is required to make such a report to the Department of Motor Vehicles, the district
32 attorney or other public agency must also make such a report the Department of Wildlife.
33 (NRS 425.510) Existing law requires the Department of Wildlife to suspend a license or
34 permit to hunt, fish or trap issued to the person named in the report, unless, within 30 days, the
35 person provides certain proof of compliance with the subpoena or warrant or satisfaction of
36 the arrearage. (NRS 502.115, 503.5835) Because section 1 changes the circumstances under
37 which the district attorney or other public agency collecting support for children may make
38 such a report to the Department of Motor Vehicles, section 4 of this bill makes conforming
39 changes to maintain the existing procedures currently in effect for making such reports to the
40 Department of Wildlife, thereby retaining: (1) the requirement that the district attorney or
41 public agency collecting support for children make reports to the Department of Wildlife; and
42 (2) the criteria under existing law for determining when a person is in arrears in the payment
43 of support for one or more children for those purposes. (NRS 425.510, 425.560) Section 3 of
44 this bill establishes the applicability of definitions.
45 Existing federal law requires each state to develop a program for the purpose of locating
46 absent parents, establishing the paternity of children and establishing and collecting payment
47 obligations for the support of children. Existing federal law makes certain federal funding and
48 payments contingent on the performance of each state in carrying out such a program. (42
49 U.S.C. §§ 651 et seq.) Existing law provides that the Administrator of the Division of Welfare
50 and Supportive Services of the Department of Health and Human Services is responsible for
51 carrying out and supervising the program of this State for those purposes. (NRS 425.365)
52 Section 2 of this bill requires the Administrator to make every effort to obtain the approval
53 necessary from the United States Department of Health and Human Services to ensure that the
54 program in this State complies with all the requirements for the receipt of such federal funds.
